<a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/nettuts?a=IyTu4QULsLg:qJokIs1kCHs:yIl2AUoC8zA"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/nettuts?d=yIl2AUoC8zA" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/nettuts?a=IyTu4QULsLg:qJokIs1kCHs:F7zBnMyn0Lo"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/nettuts?i=IyTu4QULsLg:qJokIs1kCHs:F7zBnMyn0Lo" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/nettuts?a=IyTu4QULsLg:qJokIs1kCHs:V_sGLiPBpWU"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/nettuts?i=IyTu4QULsLg:qJokIs1kCHs:V_sGLiPBpWU" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/nettuts?a=IyTu4QULsLg:qJokIs1kCHs:gIN9vFwOqvQ"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/nettuts?i=IyTu4QULsLg:qJokIs1kCHs:gIN9vFwOqvQ" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/nettuts?a=IyTu4QULsLg:qJokIs1kCHs:TzevzKxY174"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/nettuts?d=TzevzKxY174" border="0"></img></a>
</div><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/nettuts/~4/IyTu4QULsLg" height="1" width="1"/>";s:14:"date_timestamp";i:1363296205;}i:2;a:9:{s:5:"title";s:32:"Relational Databases for Dummies";s:4:"link";s:54:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/nettuts/~3/T3lvJXmX0vg/";s:8:"comments";s:91:"http://net.tutsplus.com/tutorials/tools-and-tips/relational-databases-for-dummies/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Wed, 13 Mar 2013 18:09:34 +0000";s:8:"category";s:46:"DatabasesTools & TipsTutorialsdatabaseRDBMSsql";s:4:"guid";s:32:"http://net.tutsplus.com/?p=30244";s:11:"description";s:36757:"<a
href='http://rss.buysellads.com/click.php?z=1260013&k=d754f1e9ba63a736ba8ff5ece958f7dd&a=30244&c=646694813' target='_blank'><img
src='http://rss.buysellads.com/img.php?z=1260013&k=d754f1e9ba63a736ba8ff5ece958f7dd&a=30244&c=646694813' border='0' alt='' /></a><p>Web apps can be split into two major components: a front-end that displays and collects information, and a back-end for storing the information. In this article, I&#8217;ll demonstrate what a relational database is, and how to properly design your database to store your app&#8217;s information.</p><p><span
id="more-30244"></span></p><p>A database stores data in an organized way so that it can be searched and retrieved later. It should contain one or more tables. A table is much like a spreadsheet, in that it&#8217;s made up of rows and columns. All rows have the same columns, and each column contains the data itself. If it helps, think of your tables in the same way that you would a table in Excel.</p><div
class="tutorial_image"> <img
src="http://cdn.tutsplus.com/net.tutsplus.com/authors/lalith-polepeddi/relational-databases-for-dummies-fig1.png" /></p><p><strong>Fig. 1</strong></p></div><p>Data can be inserted, retrieved, updated, and deleted from a table. The word, <em>created</em>, is generally used instead of <em>inserted</em>, so, collectively, these four functions are affectionately abbreviated as CRUD.</p><p>A relational database is a type of database that organizes data into tables, and links them, based on defined relationships. These relationships enable you to retrieve and combine data from one or more tables with a single query.</p><p>But that was just a bunch of words. To truly understand a relational database, you need to make one yourself. Let&#8217;s get started by getting some real data with which we can work.</p><hr
/><h2><span>Step 1:</span> Get Some Data</h2><p>In the spirit of the Nettuts+ Twitter clone articles (<a
href="http://net.tutsplus.com/tutorials/php/building-ribbit-in-php/">PHP</a>, <a
href="http://net.tutsplus.com/tutorials/building-ribbit-in-rails/">Ruby on Rails</a>, <a
href="http://net.tutsplus.com/tutorials/python-tutorials/building-ribbit-with-django/">Django</a>), let&#8217;s get some Twitter data. I searched Twitter for &#8220;#databases&#8221; and took the following sample of ten tweets:</p><p><strong>Table 1</strong></p><table
